Binary Search in Java

Binary Search is an efficient algorithm used to find an element in a sorted array or list.

Instead of checking every element, it repeatedly divides the search range in half.

How it works (simple idea)
Take the middle element
Compare it with the target value
If equal → found
If target is smaller → search left half
If target is greater → search right half
Repeat until found or no elements left
Important Requirement

👉 The collection must be sorted before using Binary Search.

Example
int[] arr = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9};
int target = 5;

Steps:

middle = 5 → found ✅
Java Built-in Method

Java provides a ready-to-use method:

import java.util.Arrays;

int index = Arrays.binarySearch(arr, 5);
Custom Implementation
public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
    int left = 0;
    int right = arr.length - 1;

    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = (left + right) / 2;

        if (arr[mid] == target) {
            return mid;
        } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
            left = mid + 1;
        } else {
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return -1; // not found
}
Time Complexity
Case	Complexity
Best	O(1)
Average	O(log n)
Worst	O(log n)

👉 Much faster than linear search (O(n))

When to use Binary Search

Use it when:

data is sorted
you need fast search
dataset is large
When NOT to use
data is not sorted
frequent insertions (because sorting is required)
Summary
Binary Search works only on sorted data
divides the array in half each step
very efficient: O(log n)
can be implemented manually or using Arrays.binarySearch()
